All these years of learning and studying the Sagrada Família in art histories - which I referred to as “The Melting Church” in college - and I finally am blessed with the opportunity to see it in person. And it was literally astounding, even from the outside. 

The Sagrada Família, has been under construction for 140 years, with the work beginning back in 1882. It's now in the final phase, and it is expected to be fully completed by 2030. The most recent completion being the star of the Virgin Mary. 🌟
Designed by Antoni Gaduí (obviously) who unfortunately passed away after the first set of Bell Tower spires were built, is also buried in the crypt below. 
In the Spanish Civil War, blueprints, plans, photos and molds were vandalized and destroyed. Since then, many architects have taken over the continuing construction, while doing their best to honor Gaudí’s vision. You can see the clear passing of time and hands as the Basilica builds. 

One of my favorite things and style markers of Gaudí is how his art emulates nature. Before understanding that, it’s easy to be a bit confused or put off by his maximalist work. But understanding how Gaudí made every bit of his work mirrors nature: tortoise shells, butterfly wings, ocean waves, conch shells, fruit, pine cones, bones, coral, leaves, you name it - you see the overwhelming masterpiece and mastermind wonderland work that is Antoni Gaudí. I especially love the warriors with glowing eyes and fruits and veggies over their heads. 😙👌🏼

Casa Milá by Antoni Gaudí was a marvel not to be missed in Barcelona 🇪🇸☀️. Once I was able to better grasp the beauty and genius of Gaudí after visiting la Sagrada Família, I couldn’t get enough of Gaudí’s works - not that you could hide from it in Barcelona if you tried 😍 It was actually here, in the attic of Casa Milá - which was created to resemble being swallowed by a whale and living inside its ribcage - that I learned much deeper about Gaudí’s brilliance of making art that emulates nature. Casa Milá’s breath taking and bizarre beauty with a stunning view from the top with Warrior heads that would recite poems to you in Spanish, water color murals and butterfly wing doors: was a quick, but necessary stop on my site seeing adventure. 🎨🦋🐳 #spain #barcelona #casamilá #gaudi #traveltips #arthistory

🏰📍Mount Tibidabo - definitely in my top 3 experiences in Barcelona. The feat to get to the top of the tallest mount in Barcelona was an adventure on its own, but the reward was the literally breath taking views. I was genuinely moved to tears when I reached the top amongst the Saint statues watching over the whole city. I felt so small and so blessed all at once. The ancient castle rock and winding spiral stair cases with detail carved thru out was a gorgeous gothic masterpiece. I was so badly wanting to explore every height to all of the cathedrals I had been walking amongst, and #Tibidabo more than itched that scratch. I’m so thankful I made the journey. If you are visiting #barcelona #spain, make sure you get there! 🤲🏼
